<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-424-716  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 424 716.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  May 7 1990 v36 n1808 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>US would ease exports to East Bloc. (Bush Administrationrecommends extensive trade decontrol)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Connelly, Joanne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In early May 1990 the Bush Administration recommended extensivedecontrol of the sale of telecommunications equipment andcomputers to the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.andP;  Therecommendation won only minor industry praise and a call for evengreater liberalization.andP;  Disclosure of the wide-ranging reformsfollows increased pressure from both Congress and US allies tomodernize what is considered to be an outdated and overly broadexport control policy.andP;  According to the Bush Administration,careful study shows that most of the technologies and goods thatwe currently control to Soviet and eastern Europe destinationsshould be decontrolled and are of low strategic value.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United StatesSoviet UnionComputer industryTelecommunication industryTelecommunicationsCommunications Equipment.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>